1
00:00:01,177 --> 00:00:05,985
Okay.

2
00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:24,333
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambodassam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambodassam

3
00:00:24,803 --> 00:00:33,762
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa.

4
00:00:34,223 --> 00:00:39,234
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

5
00:00:39,990 --> 00:00:54,488
I just wanted to say something extra about karma.

6
00:00:57,972 --> 00:01:03,939
Because I realized that I hadn't really made clear what the real karma is.

7
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:17,402
So if we remember that when we do an action, it has an effect into society, into the world.

8
00:01:18,463 --> 00:01:29,201
But we don't know what's going to come back to us because of surrounding conditions.

9
00:01:29,182 --> 00:01:41,621
And we don't really know the effect inwardly on our psyche.

10
00:01:43,036 --> 00:02:02,918
Now, then we have to remember what the Buddha's teaching is concerned with.

11
00:02:02,897 --> 00:02:14,313
So he's concerned with suffering and bringing suffering to an end.

12
00:02:15,014 --> 00:02:22,665
So, where is this suffering?

13
00:02:23,105 --> 00:02:26,390
It's not out in the world, it's within our own minds.

14
00:02:26,371 --> 00:02:38,044
So in terms of the process of liberation, the karma that we have to deal with is the one that's inside us.

15
00:02:39,064 --> 00:02:54,200
And remember that within us there is a given pain, you might say, mental and physical pain.

16
00:02:54,181 --> 00:03:03,430
So some of it is natural to the body, illness and so on.

17
00:03:04,211 --> 00:03:14,980
And the other is, of course, coming from our habits, from our unwholesome habits.

18
00:03:18,343 --> 00:03:21,387
Now, how we relate to that

19
00:03:21,366 --> 00:03:24,151
is also something we've taught ourselves.

20
00:03:24,912 --> 00:03:36,766
And this reaction is the direct cause of our suffering.

21
00:03:37,788 --> 00:03:48,943
And underneath that, there are these wrong views.

22
00:03:48,923 --> 00:03:51,587
So these, this is our karma.

23
00:03:51,788 --> 00:03:54,853
And this is the karma that we have to work with.

24
00:03:56,937 --> 00:04:03,627
Very good.

25
00:04:03,647 --> 00:04:06,072
So that is that.

26
00:04:06,811 --> 00:04:13,639
This, and this, and that.

27
00:04:13,658 --> 00:04:32,682
So, this evening I just want to talk about daily practice and some other things too, just because usually, especially for beginners, there's lots of questions about that.

28
00:04:32,798 --> 00:04:36,887
So remember that you've got to bring this practice into your daily life.

29
00:04:37,369 --> 00:04:48,714
And the morning sitting, the morning meditation is I think absolutely important.

30
00:04:48,694 --> 00:05:12,913
because you're setting yourself on the right path right there at the beginning of the day and at the end of the sitting where we do a reflection on the sitting

31
00:05:13,855 --> 00:05:24,944
E alla fine della seduta, quando riflettiamo sulla seduta... After that, bring to mind what is going to happen, we hope, during the day.

32
00:05:24,964 --> 00:05:31,009
E dopo di quello puoi riflettere su quello che succederà, speriamo, nel corso della giornata.

33
00:05:31,029 --> 00:05:43,862
And where you see there's a possibility of anxiety, irritation, etc., really bring it to mind and make the decision that you're going to work with that as it comes up.

34
00:05:43,841 --> 00:05:59,235
So, you know, especially at work, sometimes relationships, you know, can be pretty awful.

35
00:05:59,214 --> 00:06:27,129
sometimes we can feel overloaded by the amount of work we have so recognizing that knowing how you react to it and say to yourself right well when I get there I'll

36
00:06:27,463 --> 00:06:37,067
I'll work with it in a Dharma way.

37
00:06:38,149 --> 00:06:43,684
In other words, skillfully.

38
00:06:43,663 --> 00:06:59,766
so that's important the next point of I think important practice if you can make it into a habit is

39
00:06:59,745 --> 00:07:05,956
After the day, after a day's work or when you've been out for the day.

40
00:07:05,997 --> 00:07:18,379
And just to sit and just allow whatever accumulations have happened during the day to rise.

41
00:07:18,358 --> 00:07:27,891
So there may be anxiety, irritations, excitements.

42
00:07:28,353 --> 00:07:34,802
So just let everything, you know, cool down.

43
00:07:35,483 --> 00:07:41,851
And then you have an evening ahead of you, see?

44
00:07:41,831 --> 00:07:49,238
And this is something you can do in little bits all the way through the day.

45
00:07:49,978 --> 00:08:02,531
So this is something I brought into my own working life at the time and it reserved so much energy.

46
00:08:02,930 --> 00:08:11,838
Which was to keep stopping throughout the day and just

47
00:08:11,819 --> 00:08:16,206
Let whatever accumulation, let it exhaust itself a bit.

48
00:08:16,906 --> 00:08:33,033
Even in the mid-day break, often I wouldn't go into the staff room.

49
00:08:33,014 --> 00:08:42,388
So I would go out and sit in the local church.

50
00:08:43,149 --> 00:08:50,721
I had to always knock on the door for the...

51
00:08:51,883 --> 00:08:54,226
It was a Church of England church.

52
00:08:54,267 --> 00:08:55,589
I'd knock on the door and have the key.

53
00:08:55,609 --> 00:08:56,490
I'd give the key.

54
00:08:56,470 --> 00:09:00,134
The church in England, I knock on the door, I say, can I have the keys?

55
00:09:00,154 --> 00:09:01,296
They give me the keys.

56
00:09:01,596 --> 00:09:04,900
I say, oh, they just sit there, you know.

57
00:09:04,921 --> 00:09:11,769
Of course, churches are always quiet, they're always lovely places to sit.

58
00:09:15,553 --> 00:09:22,663
So, I think if you get into the habit of doing that, you'll see it really does save a lot of energy.

59
00:09:22,643 --> 00:09:43,149
Yes, because remember that if in the morning you become irritated with something, you know, somebody has said something to you that's irritating.

60
00:09:43,129 --> 00:09:49,139
So, you know, everybody has that experience that, you know, you're sitting there during the coffee break by yourself.

61
00:09:49,921 --> 00:09:56,972
And before you know it, the mind's off.

62
00:09:57,092 --> 00:10:03,163
You know, it's going, it's going, it's going.

63
00:10:03,865 --> 00:10:05,947
He's saying, by evening, you've got a headache.

64
00:10:05,927 --> 00:10:31,142
so it's a case of you know just being with every after every action whatever just to stop feel something just let it go so that's important now in the evening it's also really important to prepare to go to sleep

65
00:10:31,561 --> 00:10:55,729
there was a survey done in England a while back and people just aren't sleeping well and one of the reasons is that they're going to bed you know straight off Facebook

66
00:10:55,860 --> 00:11:03,182
Or a horror movie.

67
00:11:06,250 --> 00:11:11,304
So you have to allow this organism to just begin to relax.

68
00:11:11,554 --> 00:11:15,441
you have to allow your body to start relaxing.

69
00:11:15,880 --> 00:11:20,168
So half an hour before you intend to go to bed, just cool down.

70
00:11:20,589 --> 00:11:34,929
You can listen to some music, you can meditate, but you can listen to some quiet music.

71
00:11:34,909 --> 00:11:39,700
Just whatever you feel is relaxing, just drawing the energy down.

72
00:11:40,240 --> 00:11:51,484
So that would be, shall we say, a daily run of things?

73
00:11:51,464 --> 00:11:54,688
So that would be a daily routine.

74
00:11:55,049 --> 00:12:07,649
And if you can, maybe join a group once a week, once every two weeks or something.

75
00:12:07,629 --> 00:12:10,736
Because this does raise your commitment.

76
00:12:11,097 --> 00:12:23,326
The Buddha says, there's a passage where Ananda, who was the Buddha's companion for the last 20 years, looking after him,

77
00:12:23,307 --> 00:12:30,639
So the Buddha tells about Ananda who was his companion for 20 years of his life.

78
00:12:30,919 --> 00:12:45,585
He told him that for him a good companion was half of the spiritual life.

79
00:12:45,565 --> 00:12:47,528
Half the spiritual life.

80
00:12:47,869 --> 00:12:56,465
And the Buddha said, oh no, Ananda, it's all the spiritual life.

81
00:12:56,544 --> 00:13:06,222
Yes, and he points out, if you have good companions, you tend to do what is good for you.

82
00:13:06,456 --> 00:13:18,414
And remember we live in a society which is not driven by spiritual values.

83
00:13:19,176 --> 00:13:27,148
So it's very difficult to maintain that sort of spiritual view of our lives.

84
00:13:27,128 --> 00:13:37,142
I mean, if you consider, shall we say, one of these Islamic countries like Saudi Arabia.

85
00:13:38,323 --> 00:13:53,085
Now, we might not like many things about Saudi Arabia, but it is a society which is geared towards the spiritual.

86
00:13:53,065 --> 00:14:12,475
So if somebody, you know, at the prayer time, noon, I can't remember the times, but if somebody at the prayer time just stops the car, gets out of the car, puts the carpet down and starts praying, everybody thinks, oh, that's wonderful.

87
00:14:12,455 --> 00:14:25,754
Here they put you in jail.

88
00:14:25,937 --> 00:14:26,860
Or they lock you away.

89
00:14:26,919 --> 00:14:43,812
So, having to live in a society which doesn't have spiritual values makes things more difficult for us, that's all.

90
00:14:43,792 --> 00:14:50,928
And of course finally to try and get on to a retreat every year.

91
00:14:52,272 --> 00:15:01,934
Now just on that, people are always slightly concerned about progress.

92
00:15:01,914 --> 00:15:12,058
Unfortunately, spiritual progress isn't like, you know, studying a subject.

93
00:15:12,158 --> 00:15:20,278
So you get a diploma and then you get a...

94
00:15:20,258 --> 00:15:21,559
A B.A.

95
00:15:21,580 --> 00:15:22,160
and an M.A.

96
00:15:22,181 --> 00:15:23,121
and a doctorate.

97
00:15:23,142 --> 00:15:26,988
Yes, you get a diploma, then a master's, a doctorate, no.

98
00:15:27,008 --> 00:15:37,663
I mean, there are, of course, these attainments, what we call the spiritual attainments, which arise really when the time is ripe.

99
00:15:37,683 --> 00:15:45,355
There are spiritual achievements that come when the time is right.

100
00:15:45,335 --> 00:15:47,096
Yeah, you can't push them.

101
00:15:47,817 --> 00:15:59,634
But through our practice what we can begin to experience is a change in the way we relate to the life we're leading.

102
00:16:01,176 --> 00:16:11,950
So you might find that you just become, shall we say, less angry, more generous,

103
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:37,144
So this practice has a systemic effect because in a sense you've got to take whatever understanding you have and it's got to be translated into an attitude.

104
00:16:37,124 --> 00:16:46,964
So this is the Eightfold Path, you see?

105
00:16:47,565 --> 00:16:56,263
It's the Eightfold Path.

106
00:16:58,116 --> 00:17:15,990
For instance, beginning to really perceive impermanence and know that you don't have complete control over your life.

107
00:17:15,970 --> 00:17:23,607
So in the morning you remind yourself something might happen today, good and bad, and I have to be open to it.

108
00:17:24,349 --> 00:17:33,372
And to work with it.

109
00:17:33,352 --> 00:17:49,638
not try to ignore it or to try to go against what the circumstance is actually coming at you with.

110
00:17:49,618 --> 00:18:03,903
So, for instance, somebody joined the day, somebody might call you and ask for some help, but because you've set yourself on this path, you're not listening to the call, you see.

111
00:18:04,423 --> 00:18:13,298
For example, maybe during the day someone calls you because they need help, but since you've programmed your things, you don't listen to this call.

112
00:18:13,278 --> 00:18:32,451
Recognizing impermanence makes you much more malleable, able to move and change as the circumstance demands.

113
00:18:32,431 --> 00:18:38,940
And then we have to bring it into this right speech, you know, the way we speak.

114
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:55,282
I mean, most of us have given up telling great big lies, whoppers, great big lies.

115
00:18:55,464 --> 00:19:04,001
But it's surprising how we exaggerate things.

116
00:19:04,823 --> 00:19:17,186
So this borders on a mild level of dishonesty.

117
00:19:17,268 --> 00:19:26,156
Yes, and just to be aware when we're just talking for talking sake, you know, wasting time.

118
00:19:27,057 --> 00:19:45,115
That doesn't mean that you don't go through the normal pleasantries of life, such as when you meet somebody.

119
00:19:47,355 --> 00:19:50,243
And yeah, that's it really.

120
00:19:50,545 --> 00:19:51,788
And then there's right action.

121
00:19:52,651 --> 00:20:02,698
So this is to do with just remaining as close as we can to those five training rules.

122
00:20:02,678 --> 00:20:27,318
But it also has a positive side of really seeing our lives as an exercise in being virtuous.

123
00:20:29,459 --> 00:20:35,008
Our delusion manifests in the way we relate.

124
00:20:36,009 --> 00:20:45,984
So the Buddha's teaching, remember, is all about ethics.

125
00:20:47,528 --> 00:20:53,817
You can always ask yourself, what is my relationship to this, to this object?

126
00:20:53,857 --> 00:20:56,682
What is my relationship to this person and so on?

127
00:20:56,662 --> 00:21:11,518
And if you perceive it to be wholesome for yourself, for somebody else, or for both of you, then that's what we should do.

128
00:21:11,958 --> 00:21:18,965
And then there's right livelihood.

129
00:21:19,846 --> 00:21:25,452
Ah, so it's interesting that...

130
00:21:27,256 --> 00:21:37,384
It's interesting that he should include this.

131
00:21:39,270 --> 00:21:43,617
It's interesting he should include right action.

132
00:21:44,980 --> 00:21:49,006
Because it would normally be included in right action.

133
00:21:49,487 --> 00:22:05,211
But if you consider the effect on your personality and character that the job you do has upon you.

134
00:22:05,191 --> 00:22:10,579
So, for instance, the virtues that you would develop, say, as a soldier.

135
00:22:11,040 --> 00:22:16,750
As opposed to, say, being a nurse.

136
00:22:17,593 --> 00:22:22,119
Or a policeman.

137
00:22:23,261 --> 00:22:28,751
So, one of the virtues of the policeman is that he's always suspicious.

138
00:22:28,731 --> 00:22:34,603
So it affects you, doesn't it?

139
00:22:34,643 --> 00:22:36,507
It affects the way you look at the world.

140
00:22:36,968 --> 00:22:43,519
And right livelihood.

141
00:22:43,601 --> 00:22:49,592
Oh, and then the last three are to do with our practice and meditation, right concentration,

142
00:22:49,571 --> 00:22:56,766
right effort, right mindfulness, right concentration.

143
00:22:56,786 --> 00:23:10,112
And he often says, especially when you're doing something,

144
00:23:10,092 --> 00:23:30,462
He says, an awareness imbued, saturated with loving kindness.

145
00:23:30,442 --> 00:23:33,184
Even as you close the fridge door.

146
00:23:37,048 --> 00:23:38,549
With great loving kindness.

147
00:23:40,811 --> 00:24:00,450
So, if we can develop that sort of attitude in our lives, you see, you know, your heart lifts.

148
00:24:00,430 --> 00:24:03,571
You feel more happy?

149
00:24:05,205 --> 00:24:13,878
The next thing I want to point out is this virtuous circle.

150
00:24:15,421 --> 00:24:23,452
So gratitude, generosity and renunciation.

151
00:24:25,296 --> 00:24:32,866
So now if you consider just for a minute how much you've received

152
00:24:34,365 --> 00:25:02,787
from your parents from friends from society education education medicine from your practice when you actually consider how much you received you know it's impossible to pay it back

153
00:25:03,356 --> 00:25:11,387
When you realize how much you have received, you realize that it is impossible to give it back.

154
00:25:13,270 --> 00:25:28,571
The Buddha said that if you carried your parents on your shoulders the whole of your life, you would not have repaid them for the gift of life.

155
00:25:29,242 --> 00:25:32,048
This is presuming that you want to continue living.

156
00:25:37,057 --> 00:25:46,557
So, when you think about that, then of course the heart wants to try and give something back, you see.

157
00:25:46,737 --> 00:25:51,926
And this is your generosity.

158
00:25:51,906 --> 00:25:56,214
Now, you can be generous with your wealth and you can be generous with your time.

159
00:25:57,477 --> 00:26:08,396
Now, every time you give something away for the benefit of other, you could have used that for yourself.

160
00:26:08,376 --> 00:26:21,050
Every time you give away some of your wealth, well you could have used it for, you know, a day by the seaside.

161
00:26:21,570 --> 00:26:31,481
Ice cream.

162
00:26:31,461 --> 00:26:41,517
When you give your time to something, to somebody, or to any occasion, it was time that you could have used just for yourself.

163
00:26:44,260 --> 00:26:51,192
So every time you're generous, you're also practicing renunciation.

164
00:26:51,644 --> 00:27:14,470
Now, if it's to be true act of generosity with a feeling of really giving something that you didn't really want to give, then there has to be that little bit of pain.

165
00:27:15,490 --> 00:27:21,178
You say...

166
00:27:22,019 --> 00:27:30,348
And that's stretching your renunciation a bit, you see, your hold on things.

167
00:27:33,732 --> 00:27:47,048
So now in the commentaries, it doesn't say this in the actual scriptures, but the commentaries say that this is a path to liberation.

168
00:27:47,028 --> 00:27:56,163
And you can understand that if you see that the process of liberation is the process of becoming more and more non-attached.

169
00:28:01,069 --> 00:28:12,208
Just one little thing that I suffered from and I think a lot of people do

170
00:28:12,188 --> 00:28:18,493
A little thing that I have suffered, and I think many people, is that you say yes too quickly.

171
00:28:20,355 --> 00:28:27,041
For example, a friend has a lot of gardening.

172
00:28:27,442 --> 00:28:39,073
And they call you to ask you for a little help.

173
00:28:39,053 --> 00:28:41,065
And you say, oh yes, yes, yes.

174
00:28:41,085 --> 00:28:41,689
Saturday morning.

175
00:28:42,111 --> 00:28:46,396
And then afterwards you think, oh.

176
00:28:47,997 --> 00:29:16,671
and then come Saturday morning you ring them and say I have a cerebral headache so you know it's always good just to pause a moment before you say yes it's very difficult if you're in the habit of saying yes too quickly it's very difficult to say let me get back to you let me think about it

177
00:29:16,651 --> 00:29:24,404
Se sei nell'abitudine di dire subito sì, è molto difficile dire un attimo, te lo dico più tardi.

178
00:29:27,211 --> 00:29:31,178
The other thing is about love and attachment.

179
00:29:31,919 --> 00:29:35,184
Un'altra cosa è l'amore e l'attaccamento.

180
00:29:35,746 --> 00:29:39,874
So long as there's a self there will be attachment.

181
00:29:39,854 --> 00:29:58,182
And remember attachment is a dependency on something or somebody for our personal well-being, happiness, joy, etc.

182
00:29:58,348 --> 00:30:12,730
Attaccamento significa la necessità di avere qualcosa o qualcuno per essere felici e appagati So this process of generosity is helping us to let go of things

183
00:30:12,877 --> 00:30:17,663
And this process of generosity helps us to let things go.

184
00:30:18,164 --> 00:30:29,638
But when we bring that attachment into relationships then it always manifests in various ways.

185
00:30:30,779 --> 00:30:41,333
But the underlying attitude

186
00:30:41,313 --> 00:30:43,936
from attachment is one of control.

187
00:30:44,778 --> 00:30:49,944
Ma l'attitudine sottostante all'attaccamento è il controllo.

188
00:30:50,346 --> 00:31:00,180
So if your partner or your spouse doesn't do what you expect them to do then that's when you get angry.

189
00:31:00,901 --> 00:31:07,589
Se il tuo compagno o la tua compagna non fanno quello che tu vorresti ti arrabbi.

190
00:31:07,569 --> 00:31:24,313
then you get or if they if they do something that you don't expect them to do or something strange then that's when or they change they change then you get this feeling of anxiety that you're losing the person

191
00:31:24,292 --> 00:31:51,464
And I think I mentioned it before, when you stop laughing at your partner's jokes and you get bored with them, then you see you're expecting them to entertain you.

192
00:31:51,444 --> 00:32:17,030
So, if you catch your relationship, you know, you'll see when this attitude of control is coming in and that's how this attachment manifests.

193
00:32:17,010 --> 00:32:25,680
Now the opposite of that is to think that you should suffer everything because you love the person.

194
00:32:25,740 --> 00:32:36,911
Ah, and then you become the one who becomes controlled.

195
00:32:37,771 --> 00:32:46,461
So even there you've got to be clear as to what your relationship is and what you're prepared to work with.

196
00:32:46,541 --> 00:33:02,609
I mean, love doesn't mean that you allow yourself to be abused, full stop.

197
00:33:02,674 --> 00:33:05,680
It's a tricky area, you see.

198
00:33:06,721 --> 00:33:19,603
And, you know, just the attachment of a parent to a child.

199
00:33:19,634 --> 00:33:24,699
You could say it's almost natural.

200
00:33:25,500 --> 00:33:32,768
It's impossible for a parent not to have some special feeling towards their child.

201
00:33:33,188 --> 00:33:48,003
But again, notice how sometimes it manifests.

202
00:33:47,983 --> 00:33:55,192
how your child is absolutely perfect, but next door he's an absolute... You want to strangle him.

203
00:33:55,232 --> 00:34:00,339
Your child is perfect, while the one next door you'd like to strangle.

204
00:34:02,461 --> 00:34:14,818
And how, for instance, if you see your child hurt itself... For example, if you see that your child hurts himself...

205
00:34:14,797 --> 00:34:19,867
But you know, it's nothing, it's just a scratch or something, even though they're crying their eyes out.

206
00:34:19,907 --> 00:34:32,875
So then you very calmly, you know, you hug the child.

207
00:34:32,855 --> 00:34:46,148
But if you see the child may have done some real damage, they've broken their arm or banged their head badly, then there's panic.

208
00:34:47,150 --> 00:34:50,778
Then you have to ask yourself, is this panic necessary?

209
00:34:50,759 --> 00:34:55,626
And what's it doing for the child?

210
00:34:56,949 --> 00:35:03,500
Now, unfortunately, you can't stop the panic because panic, panic, panics.

211
00:35:04,442 --> 00:35:08,387
Panics.

212
00:35:08,688 --> 00:35:09,429
How do you say that?

213
00:35:09,449 --> 00:35:10,692
Panic, panic, panic.

214
00:35:11,793 --> 00:35:16,902
So...

215
00:35:16,882 --> 00:35:25,228
But as soon as somebody who meditates is aware of that, they don't allow it to completely control their actions.

216
00:35:26,449 --> 00:35:46,786
So if you keep your sensitivity open to how you're relating to people, you'll see pretty clearly where love is and where control is.

217
00:35:46,766 --> 00:36:05,652
There's one example in the scriptures where the Buddha asks these three Arahats how they live so peacefully together.

218
00:36:05,632 --> 00:36:16,103
There is a story in the scriptures that says that Buddha asked these three Arahants how they could live so peacefully.

219
00:36:16,505 --> 00:36:30,239
And he asks Anaruda, how do you maintain this peacefulness between the three of you?

220
00:36:31,164 --> 00:36:49,409
When I wake up in the morning, I say to myself, I shall put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do.

221
00:36:50,402 --> 00:37:04,664
So if you can see, if you're in a family, in your family or in a group of friends, if everybody were to say that, you can see that there's some diplomacy to go on, but eventually there wouldn't be any argument.

222
00:37:04,684 --> 00:37:11,094
You can see that if it worked in a family, there wouldn't be any discussion.

223
00:37:12,862 --> 00:37:22,407
There would be a discussion, but there wouldn't be any argument.

224
00:37:22,527 --> 00:37:30,146
Now, this only works if everybody says that to themselves.

225
00:37:32,235 --> 00:37:48,000
This putting aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do, this only really works if everybody says the same thing.

226
00:37:48,019 --> 00:37:58,074
Otherwise you'll find yourself doing what everybody else wants to do.

227
00:37:59,067 --> 00:38:08,818
But at least it gives us an idea of how we might suggest to our partners and friends how they might approach a situation.

228
00:38:09,557 --> 00:38:27,538
The other thing is to talk about these roads of success or roads of power.

229
00:38:27,518 --> 00:38:40,579
Some of you will know them, the Idipada, these things, they're called Idipada.

230
00:38:43,264 --> 00:38:50,978
When you practice in this way, with these absorptions,

231
00:38:50,958 --> 00:38:57,110
Then you can get these powers.

232
00:38:58,353 --> 00:39:02,601
You can walk through a wall.

233
00:39:03,103 --> 00:39:11,699
Now, that at first might seem ridiculous.

234
00:39:11,679 --> 00:39:23,295
But it's the ability to separate the subtle body, the mental body, from the physical.

235
00:39:23,797 --> 00:39:35,713
And the mental body is not bound by the physicality of the world.

236
00:39:35,693 --> 00:39:43,967
So perhaps you can try that this evening, eh?

237
00:39:45,429 --> 00:39:57,751
Then there's telepathy, which, believe it or not, has actually been proven as a power, you know, as proven as an ability.

238
00:39:57,731 --> 00:40:16,652
They've done experiments where certain people who do have this gift of telepathy and they've sent the other people in a submarine under...

239
00:40:16,632 --> 00:40:17,614
Down in the ocean.

240
00:40:18,295 --> 00:40:27,492
So that it can never be explained as some sort of electromagnetic manifestation.

241
00:40:27,612 --> 00:40:34,844
And yes, they were able to communicate.

242
00:40:35,025 --> 00:40:40,715
Oh.

243
00:40:42,231 --> 00:40:43,074
I forgot his name.

244
00:40:46,001 --> 00:40:46,583
It'll come to me.

245
00:40:47,746 --> 00:40:52,719
Clear audience, where you can hear things which a person would not normally hear.

246
00:40:52,958 --> 00:40:55,244
Hear people's thoughts, read their minds.

247
00:40:56,103 --> 00:41:04,751
You can bring up all your past lives.

248
00:41:05,873 --> 00:41:18,987
And you can also sometimes see the destination of people, where they're actually going to go.

249
00:41:18,967 --> 00:41:26,757
And the last one, interestingly enough, is of course the extinction of the mental intoxicants.

250
00:41:27,717 --> 00:41:32,001
L'ultima è l'estinzione degli intossicanti mentali.

251
00:41:32,563 --> 00:41:37,307
The asawa, that's what they're called, asawa.

252
00:41:37,849 --> 00:41:41,532
These three asawa, sometimes four, are...

253
00:41:41,512 --> 00:42:08,635
the basic delusions, the manifestations of that basic ignorance sense desire the desire to seek happiness through the senses the desire to become

254
00:42:08,614 --> 00:42:18,349
And wrong views, wrong understandings.

255
00:42:22,336 --> 00:42:24,739
Ignorance is also one of them.

256
00:42:25,001 --> 00:42:31,550
But the others arise out of that ignorance.

257
00:42:31,530 --> 00:42:44,945
But these qualities, the roads to success, can be used for anything in your life, and I think, yeah.

258
00:42:45,346 --> 00:43:01,182
And if you think about anything that you've really wanted to do, you'll see that these qualities were there.

259
00:43:01,432 --> 00:43:18,766
first of all there has to be that very strong desire zeal you've got to really want it secondly there has to be the effort

260
00:43:18,746 --> 00:43:21,871
to begin to manifest that desire.

261
00:43:22,112 --> 00:43:32,108
The Buddha, in the discourse on how to establish mindfulness, uses the word atapi.

262
00:43:34,311 --> 00:43:42,324
Satipatthaya, mindfulness.

263
00:43:42,304 --> 00:43:43,726
Atapi.

264
00:43:43,927 --> 00:43:49,795
And this atapi is the energy of self-mortification.

265
00:43:50,775 --> 00:43:57,123
If you, well, just a minute.

266
00:43:58,505 --> 00:44:10,742
Well, as an example, if you think of these Olympic sports people, you know,

267
00:44:10,722 --> 00:44:17,851
how much they practice every day with the goal in mind of getting that medal.

268
00:44:22,318 --> 00:44:30,248
So it also means that you've got to put your whole heart and mind into the project.

269
00:44:30,389 --> 00:44:36,518
That you can't be taken off on this little thing and that little thing.

270
00:44:37,478 --> 00:44:40,003
You're absolutely centered on what you want to achieve.

271
00:44:39,983 --> 00:45:02,615
and you've got to maintain a certain level of discrimination of investigation so if you think about that right a real determined desire

272
00:45:03,405 --> 00:45:32,215
a real effort to make that manifest a complete commitment of your heart and mind to the project and then just keeping alive that sort of you might say helpful doubt just looking for the way things are keeping in contact with the way things are moving

273
00:45:32,195 --> 00:45:40,146
E poi mantieni un sano dubbio per tenere un po' tutto sotto controllo.

274
00:45:40,306 --> 00:45:41,449
Well, yes.

275
00:45:42,630 --> 00:45:43,711
So that...

276
00:45:44,313 --> 00:45:45,034
So that...

277
00:45:45,054 --> 00:45:45,875
I don't know what's the word.

278
00:45:47,697 --> 00:45:53,746
Just maintaining a...

279
00:45:53,726 --> 00:45:59,693
Making sure that that aim is not like blinkers on a horse, you know.

280
00:45:59,753 --> 00:46:11,329
Ah, that you're aware of other things, you see.

281
00:46:12,190 --> 00:46:15,634
So I'm sure you've all done that once in your life.

282
00:46:15,614 --> 00:46:19,123
I'm sure you've all done it at least once in your life.

283
00:46:19,264 --> 00:46:19,403
Yes?

284
00:46:20,567 --> 00:46:21,510
No?

285
00:46:21,530 --> 00:46:21,690
Yes?

286
00:46:21,871 --> 00:46:22,090
No?

287
00:46:23,996 --> 00:46:27,666
So these are called the roads to success or the roads to power.

288
00:46:27,713 --> 00:46:39,289
So when you want to do something, you know, you can ask yourself, how much do I really want to do this?

289
00:46:39,369 --> 00:46:53,367
And if you feel that there's not enough desire, but you want to do it, then you have to sort of build up your desire.

290
00:46:53,827 --> 00:46:55,289
You have to cajole yourself.

291
00:46:55,269 --> 00:47:06,246
For instance, just watching the breath, you see, rising.

292
00:47:07,168 --> 00:47:08,554
You want to do it, but you...

293
00:47:09,630 --> 00:47:13,215
For example, watch your breath.

294
00:47:13,936 --> 00:47:16,740
You want to do it, but you can't really do it.

295
00:47:16,780 --> 00:47:21,347
Then you ask yourself, do I want to do it?

296
00:47:21,686 --> 00:47:28,476
And like these athletes, you have to say, yes!

297
00:47:28,777 --> 00:47:33,563
And it's like lifting weights.

298
00:47:35,297 --> 00:47:35,918
Just one more.

299
00:47:38,121 --> 00:47:39,742
Just one more.

300
00:47:41,023 --> 00:47:42,907
So you get that sort of energy.

301
00:47:43,027 --> 00:47:50,414
So this is what we're looking at when we say zeal.

302
00:47:51,376 --> 00:48:02,688
So that gives you, I hope, some ideas about daily life.

303
00:48:03,056 --> 00:48:16,177
In Zen they say if there's a separation between the meditation and daily life, by a hair's breadth you've lost the path.

304
00:48:16,538 --> 00:48:26,853
You've lost the path.

305
00:48:28,117 --> 00:48:33,784
So finally, I just want to talk about taking refuges and precepts.

306
00:48:34,626 --> 00:48:40,112
So I know some of you have done it.

307
00:48:40,914 --> 00:48:53,652
But there comes a point, I think, in a spiritual life when, in a sense, you want to make a decision about your commitment.

308
00:48:53,632 --> 00:49:13,817
So for instance, when I began practicing in Zen, after about a year, every year they do this particular ceremony,

309
00:49:13,797 --> 00:49:30,202
there was an occasion to take the refuges and precepts and I felt at the time that I had found my path

310
00:49:30,182 --> 00:49:33,467
And at that time I felt that I had found my way.

311
00:49:33,666 --> 00:49:36,329
And so I went through that ceremony.

312
00:49:36,570 --> 00:49:56,713
And just like any ceremony which punctuates our lives, it gives you a sort of starting point for a particular commitment.

313
00:49:56,693 --> 00:49:58,255
So, like for instance a marriage.

314
00:49:58,536 --> 00:50:02,483
So, you know, there's a social event in which that is proclaimed.

315
00:50:03,045 --> 00:50:11,900
And then that changes your life.

316
00:50:11,880 --> 00:50:21,157
So there comes a point in the spiritual practice where you may feel you just want to commit yourself to this path.

317
00:50:21,798 --> 00:50:32,539
So what is it that you would commit yourself to?

318
00:50:32,586 --> 00:50:38,916
Well the first thing is the Buddha.

319
00:50:41,179 --> 00:50:45,846
Now the Buddha is an exemplar and a teacher.

320
00:50:46,626 --> 00:50:54,597
Because he actually lived through this training process.

321
00:50:55,099 --> 00:51:01,648
And that's why he was able to teach it so intimately.

322
00:51:01,628 --> 00:51:06,074
And that's why he was able to teach in such an intimate way.

323
00:51:06,094 --> 00:51:29,643
So, it's a sort of understanding that the originator of this particular dispensation really was expressing what he had personally experienced.

324
00:51:30,333 --> 00:51:51,260
But spiritually, it's the Buddha within that you're taking refuge in.

325
00:51:51,240 --> 00:51:53,543
That's your real refuge.

326
00:51:54,826 --> 00:52:06,382
So there is an act of confidence that there is something in us that is seeking liberation and will attain it.

327
00:52:08,166 --> 00:52:16,858
So that's taking refuge in the Buddha.

328
00:52:17,460 --> 00:52:19,121
Taking refuge in the Dharma

329
00:52:19,101 --> 00:52:28,958
The Dhamma is both the understanding, the teachings, but also the practice.

330
00:52:29,097 --> 00:52:37,952
And I think you'll find across all Buddhisms the same basic teachings.

331
00:52:38,231 --> 00:52:46,746
There may be different interpretations, but the basic teaching remains the same.

332
00:52:46,726 --> 00:53:03,536
So the basic teachings are the Four Noble Truths, the Eightfold Path, the Dependent Origination,

333
00:53:03,516 --> 00:53:06,666
That's the psychology.

334
00:53:07,768 --> 00:53:10,717
And the three characteristics of existence.

335
00:53:11,498 --> 00:53:14,507
So that's your basis.

336
00:53:14,847 --> 00:53:18,538
I've never come across a Buddhism that doesn't teach that in some way or other.

337
00:53:18,518 --> 00:53:34,889
When it comes to the practice, there's nothing, you don't have to stay with just one practice.

338
00:53:34,869 --> 00:53:53,789
I myself moved from Zen to this vipassana and in the field of vipassana I also practiced other forms so I did some work with Goenkaji

339
00:53:54,394 --> 00:54:14,090
and also I went to certain different practices especially in Thailand but eventually I centered on this practice because this is the one that had the greatest impact on me

340
00:54:14,206 --> 00:54:30,909
And I practiced it enough to feel that I had really grasped the technique.

341
00:54:31,989 --> 00:54:34,773
So in the end I was able to just practice by myself.

342
00:54:35,114 --> 00:54:40,081
And that's of course why I teach it.

343
00:54:40,141 --> 00:54:41,563
I don't teach Zena.

344
00:54:41,695 --> 00:55:01,898
So you're taking refuge in the teaching, which means that you ought to try and lift your understanding of the Dharma.

345
00:55:02,974 --> 00:55:04,056
The understanding.

346
00:55:06,199 --> 00:55:12,809
When I started in the late 70s, there was virtually, there weren't many books on Buddhism.

347
00:55:12,829 --> 00:55:21,202
And there were hardly any talks or anything.

348
00:55:21,487 --> 00:55:27,255
Now there's a whole website.

349
00:55:30,260 --> 00:55:32,322
Yeah, absolutely.

350
00:55:32,864 --> 00:55:35,967
It's ridiculous.

351
00:55:35,987 --> 00:55:37,210
There's a book every second.

352
00:55:37,570 --> 00:55:39,994
Everybody wants to write a book.

353
00:55:40,014 --> 00:55:45,181
Yeah, even me.

354
00:55:48,487 --> 00:55:50,911
So that's the Dharma.

355
00:55:52,054 --> 00:55:58,027
And again, when I was starting, there were very few meditation centers.

356
00:55:59,931 --> 00:56:03,659
But now there's, you know, there's many.

357
00:56:04,365 --> 00:56:08,030
So the opportunity to practice is available.

358
00:56:09,291 --> 00:56:15,838
And then finally there's the taking refuge in the Sangha.

359
00:56:16,480 --> 00:56:27,672
Sangha is a technical, is a word that's used normally speaking to refer to monks and nuns.

360
00:56:27,652 --> 00:56:41,177
But these days you find it being used by the Buddhist community to refer to themselves.

361
00:56:45,025 --> 00:56:50,454
But this isn't what you're taking refuge in.

362
00:56:51,447 --> 00:57:01,423
No, neither the monks and nuns, nor... Yeah, no, don't put your refuge.

363
00:57:01,925 --> 00:57:12,762
The refuge, your confidence is in those people who have attained some insight into Nibbana.

364
00:57:12,827 --> 00:57:18,835
La tua fiducia è in quelle persone che hanno ottenuto qualche intuizione sul Nibbana.

365
00:57:18,856 --> 00:57:27,347
So, you know, we have these four levels of attainment, stream entry, once returner, non-returner, arahat.

366
00:57:27,367 --> 00:57:31,032
Ci sono quattro livelli del raggiungimento.

367
00:57:31,092 --> 00:57:31,893
Stream entry.

368
00:57:31,913 --> 00:57:34,235
Allora, l'entrare nella corrente.

369
00:57:34,675 --> 00:57:35,777
The once returner.

370
00:57:36,157 --> 00:57:37,619
Quello che ritorna una volta.

371
00:57:37,599 --> 00:57:41,427
the non-returner, and the arahat.

372
00:57:42,528 --> 00:57:55,490
So there isn't time to go into much detail about that, but these such people stand as witnesses to the Buddha's own particular experience.

373
00:57:55,471 --> 00:58:05,449
So their confidence is unshakable.

374
00:58:05,469 --> 00:58:14,744
Incorrelable.

375
00:58:17,340 --> 00:58:38,302
It is understood that if the dispensation no longer produced these people even at that level of stream entrant, it's understood that if this dispensation, if the teachings did not produce people even at that lowest level of stream entrant...

376
00:58:38,503 --> 00:58:45,710
So if these teachings didn't generate people at least at the first level of entering the current,

377
00:58:45,690 --> 00:59:10,112
the teaching would first of all corrupt into an intellectual scholastic exercise and eventually corrupt into just empty ritual

378
00:59:10,092 --> 00:59:26,177
lighting candles, bowing which, if the practice is full, has its role

379
00:59:26,157 --> 00:59:29,882
who obviously have their role in the practice.

380
00:59:30,521 --> 00:59:42,317
For those people who have more of a devotional feel towards their heart.

381
00:59:43,438 --> 00:59:50,427
More of a heart connection to the religion.

382
00:59:53,579 --> 00:59:57,782
And then, of course, there are the five precepts.

383
01:00:01,025 --> 01:00:06,751
Remember, the real translation is training, path of training.

384
01:00:07,070 --> 01:00:17,039
The real translation is the path of training.

385
01:00:18,081 --> 01:00:21,063
Pada means footstep and sika means training.

386
01:00:21,443 --> 01:00:23,585
So it's the path of training.

387
01:00:23,565 --> 01:00:29,894
So, the path would be the steps and the seeker, the seeker.

388
01:00:29,914 --> 01:00:30,516
Ah, sikha-pada.

389
01:00:30,536 --> 01:00:38,847
Sikha-pada, as it is said in the song, right?

390
01:00:38,867 --> 01:00:47,481
Pada is the steps and sikha is the training.

391
01:00:49,418 --> 01:01:09,181
So they're not commandments.

392
01:01:10,445 --> 01:01:22,724
It's not as though you should feel guilty too much if you don't follow them.

393
01:01:24,266 --> 01:01:33,599
You should feel perhaps a little disappointed that you cannot follow.

394
01:01:33,579 --> 01:01:38,244
You could feel a moment of disappointment that you didn't follow them.

395
01:01:38,606 --> 01:01:43,570
And this could lead you to encourage yourself.

396
01:01:44,592 --> 01:01:47,715
So the first one is usually very easy for us.

397
01:01:49,518 --> 01:01:56,144
We're not going to kill any living beings.

398
01:01:57,289 --> 01:02:02,059
Even this can be attenuated, in my understanding.

399
01:02:05,407 --> 01:02:12,041
I mean you have a right to protect your own life.

400
01:02:12,949 --> 01:02:21,003
And then, but what that leads us to is, of course, protecting life.

401
01:02:21,083 --> 01:02:25,650
It always moves us towards the opposite.

402
01:02:26,632 --> 01:02:31,800
And then there's not to take what is not freely given.

403
01:02:32,742 --> 01:02:39,413
So, when we...

404
01:02:39,393 --> 01:02:42,583
when we begin to practice that, it leads towards generosity.

405
01:02:45,592 --> 01:02:50,786
Now, this kamma is usually translated as sexual desire.

406
01:02:52,284 --> 01:02:55,550
The next one, not to abuse sexual desire.

407
01:02:56,070 --> 01:03:00,978
Ah, no, no.

408
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:03,782
Non abusare.

409
01:03:04,164 --> 01:03:06,407
Non abusare, sexual desire.

410
01:03:06,427 --> 01:03:11,795
But the word kamma, really in its fullness, is all sensual pleasure.

411
01:03:11,775 --> 01:03:22,253
But the word kama actually means all the sensual desires.

412
01:03:22,514 --> 01:03:32,451
And therefore also not to eat with avidity.

413
01:03:32,431 --> 01:03:34,054
So it's about indulgence.

414
01:03:34,153 --> 01:03:36,878
It's about, you know, letting go of this indulgence.

415
01:03:37,518 --> 01:03:43,367
Indulgence, yes.

416
01:03:44,309 --> 01:03:45,851
Indulgence.

417
01:03:45,871 --> 01:03:47,173
Indulgere.

418
01:03:47,934 --> 01:03:49,797
Indulgere nel piacere.

419
01:03:54,335 --> 01:03:56,697
And then there's right speech.

420
01:03:57,358 --> 01:04:00,282
This is of course the most difficult.

421
01:04:02,266 --> 01:04:03,248
Because we're always talking.

422
01:04:04,409 --> 01:04:07,653
If we're not talking to somebody, we're talking to ourselves.

423
01:04:08,335 --> 01:04:10,378
It just never stops.

424
01:04:12,740 --> 01:04:15,684
Even in dreams we're talking.

425
01:04:15,664 --> 01:04:20,309
So even though that's the most difficult, we have to make an effort.

426
01:04:20,750 --> 01:04:25,335
It should be as best as we can.

427
01:04:25,375 --> 01:04:26,335
It should be truthful.

428
01:04:27,097 --> 01:04:31,342
It should be kind, gentle.

429
01:04:32,063 --> 01:04:36,166
And we should speak at the right time.

430
01:04:38,429 --> 01:04:44,675
So if we keep that sort of ideas in our minds, then usually we're okay with right speech.

431
01:04:44,757 --> 01:04:57,393
The last one is probably the most difficult for Western society anyway.

432
01:04:59,016 --> 01:05:06,867
Not to take, you know, alcohol, drugs, whatever, that mess your level of consciousness.

433
01:05:06,947 --> 01:05:19,945
it also says in the scriptures that of course when we're under the influence of alcohol we tend to do things that we then regret

434
01:05:20,431 --> 01:05:31,972
It is also said in the scriptures that under the effects of alcohol we are subject to do things that we then regret.

435
01:05:32,233 --> 01:05:42,911
And so it depends on you how much wine you want to drink.

436
01:05:45,001 --> 01:05:50,585
You can be very strict with it, you see, no alcohol.

437
01:05:51,005 --> 01:06:00,755
Or you can be a little bit easy with it.

438
01:06:01,275 --> 01:06:14,045
It's just remembering that you want to maintain throughout our lives this bright awareness, that's all.

439
01:06:14,278 --> 01:06:27,342
I remember once I hadn't eaten all afternoon and I went to the Zen practice and on the way home I went into the pub

440
01:06:27,728 --> 01:06:30,791
and had a half a beer, just a half.

441
01:06:31,291 --> 01:06:41,643
And it was quite remarkable, I just felt this weight coming down on my brain.

442
01:06:41,663 --> 01:06:57,599
Even so, it took a while before I was able to abandon alcohol.

443
01:06:57,579 --> 01:07:03,646
And these are the refuges and precepts.

444
01:07:04,086 --> 01:07:09,994
A good practice is to start the morning by chanting or reading them.

445
01:07:10,894 --> 01:07:26,371
And then to remind yourself how you want to behave throughout the day.

446
01:07:26,351 --> 01:07:32,105
So over time you can see some progress.

447
01:07:32,846 --> 01:07:44,731
And you can rate progress by how your virtues are manifesting.

448
01:07:44,711 --> 01:07:51,389
Are you calmer?

449
01:07:51,849 --> 01:07:52,873
Are you more generous?

450
01:07:53,414 --> 01:08:00,612
Are you more open to people, etc., etc.

451
01:07:55,599 --> 01:08:00,612
?

452
01:08:01,081 --> 01:08:04,123
Are you, generally speaking, more happy with your life?

453
01:08:04,744 --> 01:08:09,509
It doesn't mean to say that trouble won't come.

454
01:08:10,309 --> 01:08:20,378
It doesn't mean that sometimes you will become very anxious or angry and so on.

455
01:08:22,661 --> 01:08:28,827
But over a long length of time, five years, twenty,

456
01:08:28,806 --> 01:08:37,720
It depends on how much you put into the practice.

457
01:08:41,046 --> 01:08:43,710
You can see some change for the better.

458
01:08:44,470 --> 01:08:50,460
If the change is for the worse, stop.

459
01:08:50,439 --> 01:09:06,564
So if over this evening and tomorrow morning you think you might want to take these Reference Precepts, then you have to fill out this little certificate for me.

460
01:09:14,355 --> 01:09:19,923
I need to know what name you want to put on my very, very lovely certificate.

461
01:09:19,904 --> 01:09:29,195
And you have to choose a virtue that you want to develop.

462
01:09:30,658 --> 01:09:33,962
But only one.

463
01:09:34,222 --> 01:09:40,411
And how long you want to take the refuges for.

464
01:09:41,011 --> 01:09:47,159
I would suggest a minimum of one year.

465
01:09:47,257 --> 01:09:57,698
One person said to me, until my birthday, I said, when's your birthday?

466
01:10:01,805 --> 01:10:02,567
In three weeks.

467
01:10:03,020 --> 01:10:07,304
I said, what's the point?

468
01:10:08,185 --> 01:10:12,189
So, I'll leave it at that.

469
01:10:12,229 --> 01:10:20,557
The other thing is that on Saturday evening, we have an opportunity to answer any questions that come up.

470
01:10:21,037 --> 01:10:22,960
And so, there's a leaf here.

471
01:10:23,079 --> 01:10:25,403
You can just write your questions up.

472
01:10:25,462 --> 01:10:32,470
Yeah, see?

473
01:10:33,884 --> 01:11:02,506
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused even greater confusion, that by your devotion to your practice, you will be liberated from all suffering, sooner rather than later.

474
01:11:06,385 --> 01:11:09,173
Oh just on time.

